column1: some of the bravest things i've done in my life required a courage i didn't know i had. when i initially found this quote in an interview with @gilliana it spoke volumes to me at a time when i was dealing with some pretty deep and intense stuff from my past. she was gracious enough this summer to write it out for me and i'm happy to wear it as a reminder of all that i've overcome and to encourage me to press on through the fear to come. thanks @truthandtriumphtattoo and @robertlamb for making it a reality.

column1: you can watch the superbowl and still understand why people are taking a knee... you cannot watch the superbowl and still love the sport...
don't join in on something because it's trending... know why people are taking a knee... know why people are choosing to not watch the superbowl... .
i hope this video gives some insight into why some of us choose to take a knee... click on the link in bio for the full video!

it's a 3 minute video and i would love for you all to get the entire scope of what i'm saying... this is a divisive  issue... but it is a real issue that people are literally losing their life over... it's not about being disrespectful to the flag... it's about racial inequality and police brutality... that has always been the narrative despite those who seek to highjack it... if you disagree i still love you... but ask yourself why you disagree... and really be honest about it... let me know if you are more vocal about flag kneeling than police killings... but most importantly let me know if you have anything to add to the conversation... at the end of the day it's about equality and unity...";;en;;;;;;0;;monti_washington;Monti Washington;;0;False;2;0;0;21;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/7723e2f4da60323b33ebb1a4459fb165/5C7E3F57/t51.2885-15/e35/50572337_353123808751315_9096175974845804515_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"lets keep it 100!

column1: 49108;instagram;2019-02-03 21:04:33;FALSE;"i have always been a feminist - having a baby recently has made me a slightly angrier one.. why.. oh so many reasons. women are reduced so often as being the fairer sex
column2: the weaker sex. yet women are the lifegivers and any person who can push another human out of their vagina and then mind the most vulnerable thing in the world is so far from weak. it is patriarchal society's view of women as lesser than - down to diminishing women's interest in relationships in culture to 'chick lit' or 'chick flicks' while melodramatic stories based on male characters and drugs or sex or murder reign supreme. it is in the increasingly pornographical norms of the images we constantly consume - women as placid pretty objects for men's pleasure. it is the regulation of child rearing as *just* minding a child at home with little government support (tho ireland better than many countries) and not tying in the importance of creating mentally and physically  healthy children who will go on to be stable adults all for the betterment of wider society. it is the sheer ridiculousness of how we value work over family possessions over poetry. i work in a hospice and believe me your family and a prayer or at least some nice words are what matters in the end. women are so much closer to this through nature in my opinion and we have been quashed through religion and patriarchy for so long. because of fear fear fear. fear of how great and immense and powerful women really are. no more.  no more.

column1: 49141;instagram;2019-02-03 20:26:14;TRUE;;"#repost from @leslehonore with @regram.app ... today in black history we honor the silence
we the silent screams of our foremothers
the screams tucked into the darkest places
so as not to wake the children
and see more horror in their eyes
so as not to wake the men
and see the pain of not being able to protect us
we the words that didn‚Äôt part from our teeth
we did best to know our place
we did best not to be uppity
or think that we may deserve dignity
we that learned a down cast eye
we the tears flowing like waterfalls
our feet bleed beneath our skin
our tongue tattooed with perpetual bite
we learned to suffer in silence to save ourselves
to save our men and children
with the screams of our ancestors at our backs
vengeance that has laid waiting for too long
and you will never hear the same again
our screams will echo in your souls forever
for as long as you can
but move when you hear my army
move when you hear my battle cry
move when you feel the presence of my lineage

my strange habit is that i often read books without knowing much about the plot because i don‚Äôt read the synopsis. i like the idea of just opening a book with my mind open to all the possibilities of the story. funny thing is
column2: sometimes i find things in the book that surprise me which i would‚Äôve known about if i read the synopsis. i do this with books that i either buy because i like the cover or are recommended to me. this was the case with beartown. all i knew was it was about a town that loved hockey and that it had criticisms of the world we live in.

i felt so very canadian reading it just because it was about hockey. but later on the book sort of took a dark turn that i wasn‚Äôt expecting (but it‚Äôs in the synopsis!). it was an emotional rollercoaster for sure which made me both sad and angry. but it is a necessary and
column5: especially in the #metoo era. i loved maya so much

49174;instagram;2019-02-03 19:48:46;FALSE;#metoo i am a rape survivor. when i was 13 i was raped by a boyfriend and after my ordeal i went home and ate dinner with my family like nothing happened. i know why. it was because of #rapeculture and the conspiracy of shame that i remained silent. look how cute i was ffs. maybe it was my own fault anyway? some of the people who i did tell and who found out also stayed silent because they assumed i enjoyed and liked it... to be clear i did not. these photos were scrapbooked into my journal around the time of that brutal attack. i loved journaling. i think i have a few entries in this journal that mention the rape but not many as i didn‚Äôt like to write about it. the photo when you scroll across was me at prom when i was about to turn 17. that was the night i lost my virginity to one of my school friends willingly. because you don‚Äôt lose your virginity by being raped. after the rape a darkness descended on my soul which has taken a long time to start to lift. i will probably fight this shadow for the rest of my life. the important thing is now i am ready to heal and move on as an addict and codependent person in recovery

column1: im using this platform as a diary almost ... documentation of life...i've been documenting my life since i was 15/16 and my mind 'snapped' at that time all the past trauma and current trauma was too much to handle....i don't think i'll ever be the person i was before 15/16...i don't remember that period much anyways....10 years later it's got better for me...now i'm not saying life is all peachy cuz it's not....i have days where i go to work shut my office door and cry and let this panic attack run it's course....i attempted suicide at 18...no one believed me when i explained my motives for behavior (ie: cutting myself
column2: walking out of the home and wandering around just to get away)...everyone thought i was just a spoiled kid...i was always dismissed...i'm an adult now and am going to use my voice !

column1: introduction: hi all. i'm 26 years old. my names stephanie. mental illness specifically depression anxiety disassociation...ptsd hit me hard when i was 15.

i come from a conservative haitian mother+family(father's side is west african.. i have nothing to do with that side) they don't know i identify as lesbianüë≠üè≥Ô∏è‚Äçüåà (i mentioned it to my mom when i was in college and she told me not to embarrass her +catholic family or put that 'shame' on them i'm an abomination) and attribute  my mental health symptoms as a character flaw..(note to everyone: mental  illness is not your fault) and being lesbian as the devil's spawnüôÑ idc anymore..i'm me nd will continue to thrive as best as i can in this life... i work as a professional but feel such a lack of connection to others in real life... withdrawal from socialization started at 16.
i'm a survivor: child physical emotional and sexual abuse.

i still fight everyday despite the crippiling panic attacks. i want to let others who went going through shit that it can get better and you are in controlüí™üèøüí™üèºüí™üí™üèªüí™üèæüí™üèΩ please message me if you'd like or have something in common with me‚ô•Ô∏è i can talk more about my story if you all want... #introduction #lesbian #mentalillness  #childsexualabusesurvivor #csa #abuse survivor #ptsd #depression #anxiety #life #motivation #hope #support #weareallonefamily #youareneveralone #metoo #haitanamerican #lonely #isolated #isurvived #itgetsbetter";;en;#introduction

column1: 49349;instagram;2019-02-03 17:04:48;FALSE;"former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel
column2: but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

column1: in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23
column2: flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia
column3: and kushner spoke with kim darroch
column4: the british ambassador to the united states
column5: according to diplomats familiar with the conversations
column6: who spoke on condition of anonymity.

column1: the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump
column2: who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric
column3: took office on jan. 20. it failed
column4: with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

column1: the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move
column2: egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution
column3: prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

column1: a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a ""high level"" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.
according to court documents made public on friday
column2: a member of trump's presidential transition team
column3: later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner
column4: told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments
column6: to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

49627;instagram;2019-02-03 13:10:14;FALSE;today in black history we honor the silence
we the silent screams of our foremothers
the screams tucked into the darkest places
so as not to wake the children
and see more horror in their eyes
so as not to wake the men
and see the pain of not being able to protect us
we the words that didn‚Äôt part from our teeth
we did best to know our place
we did best not to be uppity
or think that we may deserve dignity
we that learned a down cast eye
we the tears flowing like waterfalls
our feet bleed beneath our skin
our tongue tattooed with perpetual bite
we learned to suffer in silence to save ourselves
to save our men and children
with the screams of our ancestors at our backs
vengeance that has laid waiting for too long
and you will never hear the same again
our screams will echo in your souls forever
for as long as you can
but move when you hear my army
move when you hear my battle cry
move when you feel the presence of my lineage

column1: 49764;instagram;2019-02-03 08:36:46;FALSE;"i finally received some sort of a case ""update"" after months of complete silence only to hear that the detective still hasn't contacted the state laboratory about my rape kit when it's been over a year and that he's been sick for a few weeks
column2: which is apparently his reason for not speaking to me or my attorney since october. i get my hopes up at the possibility of an update only to find out that that he wants to reinterview me...again. what the actual fuck. i have given six statements. there isn't anything about that night that i haven't answered multiple times already. at this point i am just trying to pick up the pieces of my life and heal and i feel like this is just dragging me back over and over. i don't want to lose hope but it has been 14 months since my attack and i am no closer to justice than i was the morning i sat in a hospital bed getting my rape kit done. nothing has been done to protect me and the other women he will inevitably hurt. i am beginning to wonder if it is naive to think anything will ever be done and if this entire process hasn't been a complete waste of time.

column1: 49983;instagram;2019-02-03 02:49:58;FALSE;he was a monster. no one believed me. one day i went to a pastor who had the reputation for being against divorce. i wanted him to tell me what i was doing wrong!  i shared with him my reasons...well
column2: some of them as he never let me finish. he offered to pay for the divorce right there
column3: and the look on his face scared me. i knew i was in grave danger. divorce brought shame to the family and my father stopped speaking to me for years. my mother scolded me and sided with him. i was alone
